{"cursor":"2966","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox MP\n| name=Sir Arunachalam Mahadeva honorific-prefix = honorific-suffix = KCMG\n| nationality=Ceylonesen image = imagesize =250px order1=Minister of Home\n| Affairs of the State Council term_start1= 1942 term_end1= 1946 predecessor1=\n| successor1= order2=Ceylon's High Commissioner to India term_start2= 1949\n| term_end2=1950 order3= birth_date=5 October 1885 birth_place=Colombo, Ceylon\n| dead= death_date=8 June 1969 death_place=Colombo, Ceylon spouse= party=\n| vicepresident= religion= alma_mater =Royal College, Colombo occupation\n| =diplomat, legislator profession =\n}}\n\nSir 'Arunachalam Mahadeva', {{Abbr (5 October 1885 - 8 June 1969) was a Sri\nLankan, prominent colonial era legislator and diplomat. He was Minister of Home\nAffaires [http://www.island.lk/2001/07/18/midwee08.html Sir Don Baron\nJayatilaka â a great legacy] of the State Council and Ceylon's High\nCommissioner to India.\n\nThe son of prominent leader Sir Ponnambalam Arunachalam, Arunachalam Mahadeva\nwas educated, like his father, at the prestigious Royal College Colombo.\n\nHe was elected as a member of the Legislative Council of Ceylon and to the State\nCouncil. He became the Home Minister when D. S. Senanayake became Leader of the\nHouse. From 1948 to 1950 he served as Ceylon's High Commissioner to India.\n\nHis son-in-law is Professor T. Nadaraja.\n","linknr":123,"url":"Arunachalam_Mahadeva","recorded":1375088049,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Arunachalam_Mahadeva&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Arunachalam_Mahadeva&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs